nged our understanding of the relationship between subjective, intersubjective, and objective, and shed new light on concepts such as externalism, internalism, communication, interpretation, and language. At the same time, however, it has been strongly criticized for several aspects. The papers collected in this volume-written by established contributors-aim to provide new insights into the contemporary debate on triangulation. The upshot is not only a deeper understanding of Davidson’s ideas but also a new appreciation of some central problems of epistemology and the philosophy of mind with regard to adjoining disciplines such as, for instance, cognitive sciences and the philosophy of language.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aExternalism (Philosophy of mind). 0aPhilosophy of mind. 0aSkepticism. 4aDonald Davidson. 4aErkenntnistheorie. 4aPhilosophie des Geistes. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aAmoretti, M. Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmoretti, Maria Cristina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBar-On, Dorit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Caro, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFergestad, Ingvald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Sanford C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudwig, Kirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalpas, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreyer, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreyer, Gerhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPriselac, Matthew, econtribut